  "summary": "# Security Analysis Report: PyYAML 5.3\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nPyYAML 5.3 contains **CRITICAL** arbitrary code execution vulnerabilities (CWE-502: Deserialization of Untrusted Data, CWE-94: Code Injection) that allow attackers to execute arbitrary Python code when parsing untrusted YAML input.\n\n## Critical Findings\n\n### 1. Arbitrary Code Execution via Unsafe Deserialization (CRITICAL - CWE-502)\n\n**Severity**: Critical  \n**CWE**: CWE-502 (Deserialization of Untrusted Data), CWE-94 (Code Injection)\n\n#### Vulnerability Details\n\nPyYAML 5.3 implements dangerous YAML tag handlers that enable arbitrary Python object construction and code execution:\n\n**Dangerous Tag Handlers Found (10 instances across lib/ and lib3/):**\n- `tag:yaml.org,2002:python/name:` - Can reference any Python function/class\n- `tag:yaml.org,2002:python/module:` - Can import arbitrary modules  \n- `tag:yaml.org,2002:python/object:` - Can instantiate arbitrary objects\n- `tag:yaml.org,2002:python/object/new:` - Can create new object instances\n- `tag:yaml.org,2002:python/object/apply:` - Can apply functions with arguments\n\n**Dangerous Constructor Methods (22 instances):**\n- `find_python_module()` - Uses `__import__()` to dynamically import modules\n- `find_python_name()` - Uses `__import__()` to resolve Python names\n- `construct_python_name()` - Constructs Python objects from names\n- `construct_python_module()` - Constructs module objects\n- `make_python_instance()` - Creates arbitrary Python instances\n- `construct_python_object()` - Constructs arbitrary Python objects\n- `construct_python_object_apply()` - Applies functions to arguments\n- `construct_python_object_new()` - Creates new object instances\n\n**Dynamic Import Usage (4 instances):**\n- `__import__()` calls found in `lib/yaml/constructor.py` (lines 520, 540)\n- `__import__()` calls found in `lib3/yaml/constructor.py` (lines 513, 533)\n\n#### Attack Scenario\n\nAn attacker can craft malicious YAML input to execute arbitrary code:\n\n```yaml\n!!python/object/apply:os.system\nargs: ['malicious_command']\n```\n\nor\n\n```yaml\n!!python/object/new:subprocess.Popen\nargs: [['malicious', 'command']]\n```\n\nThis allows complete system compromise when parsing untrusted YAML data.\n\n#### Impact\n\n- **Remote Code Execution (RCE)**: Attackers can execute arbitrary system commands\n- **Data Exfiltration**: Sensitive data can be stolen\n- **System Compromise**: Full control over the application and underlying system\n- **Privilege Escalation**: Can be used to gain elevated privileges\n\n#### Affected Components\n\n- `lib/yaml/constructor.py` (Python 2 version)\n- `lib3/yaml/constructor.py` (Python 3 version)\n- All loader classes that inherit from `UnsafeConstructor` or `FullConstructor`\n\n## Recommendations\n\n1. **NEVER use `yaml.load()` with untrusted input** - This uses the unsafe Loader by default\n2. **Use `yaml.safe_load()` instead** - This only constructs simple Python objects (strings, lists, dicts)\n3. **Upgrade to PyYAML 5.4+** - Later versions changed the default behavior\n4. **Input Validation**: If unsafe loading is absolutely necessary, validate and sanitize all YAML input\n5. **Sandboxing**: Run YAML parsing in isolated, sandboxed environments with minimal privileges\n\n## Conclusion\n\nPyYAML 5.3 contains well-known, critical arbitrary code execution vulnerabilities through its unsafe deserialization mechanisms. The library's design intentionally allows Python object construction from YAML, which is extremely dangerous when processing untrusted input. Organizations using this version should immediately upgrade and audit all YAML parsing code to ensure `safe_load()` is used exclusively for untrusted data.",
